ive, social, economic, and cultural facets of the First Empire. He begins with the domestic program and institutions under Napoleon and the fervor of the new chief of state as he sought to establish a coherent, efficient, and thoroughly controlled regime. Bergeron then examines the opposition to his system and the reasons behind the imperfect realization of his ideal. It discusses population and demographic trends, social structure, and economic activity—all of which eluded Napoleon's grasp.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh  aAnnexation.  aAristocracy.  aBanditry.  aBattle of Marengo.  aBattle of Wagram.  aBonapartism.  aBourgeoisie.  aBrumaire.  aCapitalism.  aCauses of the French Revolution.  aCharter of 1814.  aCivil service.  aCommittee of Public Safety.  aConscription.  aConstitution of the Year VIII.  aController-General of Finances.  aCounter-revolutionary.  aCoup of 18 Brumaire.  aEconomics.  aEdict of Nantes.  aEmployment.  aEstates-General of 1789.  aExpense.  aFrench Consulate.  aFrench Directory.  aFrench campaign in Egypt and Syria.  aFrench nobility.  aGovernment debt.  aIdeology.  aIncome.  aIndustrialisation.  aInstitution.  aIntendant.  aJacobin.  aJean-Baptiste Say.  aJoseph Bonaparte.  aJoseph de Maistre.  aJuste milieu.  aLegion of Honour.  aLegislature.  aLouis XVIII of France.  aLucien Bonaparte.  aMarc Bloch.  aMysterium Coniunctionis.  aNantes.  aNapoleon.  aNobility.  aNotary.  aParlement.  aPolitics.  aPopular sovereignty.  aPrinting.  aProclamation.  aReligion.  aReturn to normalcy.  aRobert Nozick.  aRomanticism.  aSalary.  aSeigneur.  aSinking fund.  aSocial history.  aSubtle body.  aTax.  aThe Other Hand.  aThe Social Contract.